Playaeton MP01: Arduino IDE & nice!nano Setup Guide
Date Modified: May 3, 2026

Step 1: Install the Arduino IDE
If you haven't already, download and install the latest version of the Arduino IDE.
    • Where: arduino.cc/en/software
    • Tip: Version 2.0 or higher is recommended for a much smoother experience.

Step 2: Add the Board Manager URL
The Arduino IDE doesn't know what a "nice!nano" or "nRF52" is by default. You have to tell it where to find the "blueprints" for those chips.
    1. Open Arduino IDE.
    2. Go to File > Preferences.
    3. Look for the box labeled Additional Boards Manager URLs.
    4. Paste this link into the box:
       [https://adafruit.github.io/arduino-board-index/package_adafruit_nrf52_index.json](https://adafruit.github.io/arduino-board-index/package_adafruit_nrf52_index.json)
    5. Click OK.

Step 3: Install the nRF52 Board Core
Now that the IDE knows where to look, you need to actually download the software that talks to your chip.
    1. Go to Tools > Board > Boards Manager...
    2. In the search bar, type nRF52.
    3. Find Adafruit nRF52 by Adafruit and click Install.
        ◦ Note: This might take a few minutes as it installs the compilers and tools.

Step 4: Install the Bluefruit Library
Your code uses #include <bluefruit.h>, which is a specific library for Bluetooth functions.
    1. Go to Sketch > Include Library > Manage Libraries...
    2. Search for Adafruit Bluefruit nRF52.
    3. Click Install. If it asks to install "Dependencies" (other tiny libraries it needs), click Install All.

Step 5: Select Your Board and Port
Now you need to tell the IDE exactly which hardware is plugged into your computer.
    1. Plug in your nice!nano via USB.
    2. Go to Tools > Board > Adafruit nRF52 Boards > nice!nano.
        ◦ If you don't see nice!nano, selecting Adafruit Feather nRF52840 Express usually works as they share the same brain.
    3. Go to Tools > Port and select the one that appears when you plug in your board (e.g., COM3 or /dev/cu.usbmodem...).

Step 6: Upload the Code
You are ready to go!
    1. Copy the MP01 code you have.
    2. Delete everything in the Arduino IDE window and paste your code.
    3. Click the Upload button (the arrow pointing to the right $\rightarrow$ in the top left corner).
    4. Watch the "Output" window at the bottom. Once it says "Device programmed" or "Upload successful", your device is alive!

Helpful Tips for Beginners
    • The Serial Monitor: After uploading, go to Tools > Serial Monitor. Set the speed to 115200 baud. You will see the "System Starting..." message here!
    • Double-Tap Reset: If the computer won't "see" your board, quickly double-tap the tiny Reset button on the nice!nano. The LED will start pulsing green/red, putting it into "Bootloader Mode" so you can upload code.
    • Mobile App: To see the Bluetooth messages, download the Adafruit Bluefruit Connect app on your iPhone or Android. Connect to "Playaeton-MP01" and go to the UART section.
